contemporary
political map.

BAA7728081944A5F981328BA19E0304F.description:
Colonialism and imperialism
led to the spread of nationalism
and influenced contemporary
political boundaries.

B8ACFDE3A4204CB1A8A675E099334485.description:
The concept of the modern
nation-state began in Europe.

D64B501336B544A984804421E10528CF.description:
Explain the evolution
of the contemporary
political map.

BCDDCF6906D345BB94A2D87638323F66.description:
Types of political entities include
nations, states, nation-states,
stateless nations, multinational
states, multistate nations,
and autonomous regions.

AA7A7F0AB0214902B63A367C6A3C2B5E.description:
Independent states are the
primary building blocks of
the world political map.

96B18D07B60D457A929322A0AFEB918D.description:
Explain the structure
of the contemporary
political map.

0996E35C99C2454F8F9B95FA115F38FF.description:
The contemporary
political map has
been shaped by
events of the past.

17371932592C49EF88F116929A56BBBC.description:
Popular culture origins are
often urban, changeable,
and influenced by media.

ED0FEBCB5772464EBB7E70614DC38343.description:
Folk culture origins are usually
anonymous and rooted in tradition
and are often found in rural or
isolated indigenous communities.

C035CE5730C3469DAE9068873FEEED7F.description:
Compare and contrast
popular and folk
culture and the
geographic patterns
associated with each.

B8FE25921A3848D59C49F6D4A60D24B7.description:
Cultural landscapes are
amalgamations of physical
features, agricultural and
industrial practices, religious
and linguistic characteristics,
and other expressions of
culture (e.g., architecture).

65C644E350CB44C8933CAF93FA93847A.description:
Explain how culture
is expressed in
landscapes and how
land and resource
use represents
cultural identity.

6BBBE01B91764F6AA9AAEDDE9B18D5EE.description:
Universalizing religions (e.g.,
Christianity, Islam, Buddhism)
are spread through expansion
and relocation diffusion.

7C04FC7C0A994AE9A2184811FD8C5186.description:
Ethnic religions (e.g., Hinduism,
Judaism) are generally found
near the hearth or spread
through relocation diffusion.

BCF790BD259B40829C7B9618363DB258.description:
Compare and
contrast ethnic
and universalizing
religions and their
geographic patterns.

459ADA27A0D94F58BE23D623DAC77F1D.description:
Acculturation, assimilation, and
multiculturalism are shaped
by the diffusion of culture.

F7CEEB8D85D543FB8687B03868F7418D.description:
Colonialism, imperialism,
and trade helped to shape
patterns and practices of culture
(e.g., language, religion).

81360F96B1094385872B9A8D4A6F3B8F.description:
Language families, languages,
dialects, world religions, ethnic
cultures, and gender roles
diffuse from cultural hearths,
resulting in interactions between
local and global forces that
lead to new forms of cultural
expression (e.g., lingua franca).

121E2F364AA94ECE97855696516EC5E9.description:
Types of diffusion include
expansion (contagious, hierarchical,
stimulus) and relocation.

839A8097ACB34EF29B0FD45EC5C162EB.description:
Explain the diffusion
of culture and
cultural traits through
time and space.

41E23BF5C480465C8BC33A8DC8F7333A.description:
Language, religion, ethnicity,
and gender are essential to
understanding landscapes symbolic
of cultural identity (e.g., signs,
architecture, sacred sites).

93E8740F222D4D69A0A6D150C7ADAAA2.description:
Ethnicity and gender reflect
cultural attitudes that shape the
use of space (e.g., women in the
workforce, ethnic neighborhoods).

106AB9823136450BBD547A336A8CFC68.description:
Religious patterns and
distributions can be represented
on maps and charts.

1EA800DF8D73423A80458B64525B1507.description:
Language patterns and distributions
can be represented on maps,
charts, and language trees.

18690D19B9574498BD6BCE235479212B.description:
Regional patterns of language,
religion, and ethnicity contribute
to a sense of place, enhance
place making, and shape the
global cultural landscape.

BA09B39CA9084C78A7ED92DD13F684AB.description:
Explain cultural
patterns and
landscapes as
they vary by place
and region.

E9CE8B7EA5D74BACBA449055E0AAB0E5.description:
Culture varies by
place and region.

644CE49F76C3416FAD1735D943750F5B.description:
Communication technologies
(e.g., the Internet) are reshaping
and accelerating interactions
among people and places and
changing cultural practices
(e.g., use of English, loss of
indigenous languages).

452A0BC7788F4F3B9EC0076F0DD65DE7.description:
Explain how
globalization is
influencing cultural
interactions
and change.

1671541E5535453A89A8785636FE38FE.description:
Geographers use maps and the
spatial perspective to analyze
and assess language, religion,
ethnicity, and gender.

10604965EB704877B3AE1377644AA67E.description:
Explain how
geographers assess
the spatial and
place dimensions of
cultural groups in the
past and present.

4346E3BB50394A05AEDD748F03EC13BF.description:
Cultural traits are individual
elements of culture and include
such things as food preferences,
architecture, and land use.

EED81ECBC2EF4CB9BA0EE2D7E86464A3.description:
Culture is comprised of the
shared practices, technologies,
attitudes, and behaviors
transmitted by a society.

B8175107B27C4EC69D55E3FF7B6C7FE5.description:
Explain the concept
of culture and identify
cultural traits.

19C3D7826B594B028FA9FCD5578965C9.description:
Concepts of culture
frame the shared
behaviors of a society.

1C1143BE57744987AA5E911B43F25A34.description:
Migration has consequences
(e.g., remittances; spread of
languages, religions, innovations,
diseases) for areas that generate
or receive migrants.

7F1E6B0157EA4ED7A94C4B5A738951CC.description:
Governments institute policies to
encourage or restrict migration.

AE0B18A488F34A90A8E2F5C84247CE1F.description:
Analyze the
cultural, economic,
environmental, and
political consequences
of migration.

359DA6A03984468589E0128C1261A023.description:
Major historical migrations include
forced migration of Africans to
the Americas, immigration waves
to the U.S., and emigration from
Europe and Asia to colonies abroad.

48DC9D9E3E114C92962C46ABE651E8F0.description:
Patterns of voluntary and forced
migration may be affected by
distance and physical features.

6417A5E4E5274868A230F23602F8E2BE.description:
Voluntary migrations may be
transnational, internal, chain,
step, and rural to urban.

275A73F9A89C4B2286B872863D585692.description:
Forced migrations include
those involving refugees,
internally displaced persons,
and asylum seekers.

A398B27BFAB34CD58689B5BCB33CE817.description:
Apply the concepts of
forced and voluntary
migration to historical
and contemporary
examples.

A1BF342A26054AA3A258A0CDD7459FE0.description:
Push factors are often negative
(e.g., poor economic conditions,
warfare), while pull factors are
often perceived as positive
(e.g., a better quality of life,
economic opportunities).

3AC46AE4249C4103963B52A51D1FF4C5.description:
Push and pull factors can be
cultural (e.g., religious freedom),
demographic (e.g., unbalanced sex
ratios, overpopulation), economic
(e.g., jobs), environmental
(e.g., natural disasters), or
political (e.g., persecution).

3300B544687A4078B9EF172043197D7C.description:
Explain how push and
pull factors contribute
to migration.

FC87466297864DCA9A540FB537B04C4E.description:
Causes and
consequences
of migration are
influenced by cultural,
demographic,
economic,
environmental, and
political factors.

A072D68E5B9843A1AD67043DC03C147A.description:
An aging population has social
(e.g., retirement), economic (e.g.,
dependency ratio), and political
(e.g., voting patterns) implications.

286B5B7846314B1A86D047B0D97F84B3.description:
Population aging is influenced
by birth and death rates
and life expectancy.

28FC30742C174CE1BC1859CA82A15FC8.description:
Explain the causes
and implications of
an aging population.

68CC23FF708C4659A45A682B8893DB69.description:
Changing social, economic, and
political roles for women have
influenced the patterns of fertility,
mortality, and migration.

DDD07227C1424472AA18723E1F5EFAF2.description:
Changing social values and
access to education, employment,
health care, and contraception
have reduced fertility rates in
most parts of the world.

668EB3961F0F43988B594FE3D90C71FA.description:
Analyze reasons for
changes in fertility
rates in different
parts of the world.

CCB62837C7704FC9914DD0F3CD3F4A69.description:
Types of population policies
include those that promote or
restrict population growth (e.g.,
pronatalist, antinatalist).

A2836AB8D6CB4706991AF87AB391EC06.description:
Evaluate various
national and
international
population policies.

44655A808F0E4661B6287FC288213813.description:
The epidemiologic
transition explains causes
of changing death rates.

94FB8A8CE96249408F5BD5316D08B89E.description:
Malthusian theory is used to
analyze population change
and its consequences.

FB93A6FB4DA64D1C8B6FF16D377E98AB.description:
The demographic transition model
may be used to explain population
change over time and space.

61B146CA86F04BA7822F79DE830DFD66.description:
Interpret and apply
theories of population
growth and decline.

73042BB492A74FAE8A7F9D729EB61A04.description:
Social, cultural, political, and
economic factors influence fertility,
mortality, and migration rates.

E196D9C522AF47908812DA49F3FFBB1C.description:
Rates of natural increase and
population-doubling times are
used to explain population
growth and decline.

2D615EB6CF0A436090D524B5BF0405A6.description:
Demographic factors that determine
population growth and decline are
fertility, mortality, and migration.

E86CCDE4BFDE424AB062823C277FF371.description:
Explain contemporary
and historical trends
in population growth
and decline.

ED593EC5CF4A4085B15BA57EE9191734.description:
Populations grow
and decline over
time and space.

FCE78AFFC158423BBF07883BD543D85D.description:
Population pyramids are used to
project population growth and
decline and to predict markets
for goods and services.

5F3282E8876548069B3AED4EE986EA82.description:
Age, sex, and ethnicity are
elements of population
composition that may be mapped
and graphed at various scales.

61D67FD3BDCA4659A22C0EC41EB57B5D.description:
Population distribution and
density affect the need for
infrastructure (e.g., housing) and
urban services (e.g., sanitation).

3862F3E2AE8C45859D81D88E1C7B16C8.description:
Population distribution and density
impact the environment and natural
resources (e.g., carrying capacity).

551AF34C8053468A8648164340ECC50E.description:
Population distribution and
density influence political,
economic, and social processes
(e.g., redistricting, provision of
services such as medical care).

0CACCDAD070945F8A1D4AB27E301838C.description:
Explain the
implications
of population
distributions and
densities.

20B69506CDA344CFA2056F29CF5328ED.description:
The three methods for calculating
population density are arithmetic,
physiological, and agricultural.

92A6522E63E84B5698019B8800EF1D7E.description:
Use population
density to explain
the relationship
between people and
the environment.

59A353A1805F452980253EAE8EEAE5A9.description:
Physical factors (e.g., climate, land
forms, water bodies) and human
factors (e.g., cultural, economic,
historical, political) influence
the distribution of population.

11082354FD704411B3469A4799638A08.description:
Factors that explain patterns
of population distribution
vary according to the scale of
analysis (i.e., local to global).

F7EBD3E3ED964DCAB1CF4D594116918B.description:
Analyze the
distribution of
human populations
at different scales.

D8D84208D263424FA217372ACE83B1F5.description:
Knowledge of the
geographic patterns
and characteristics of
human populations
facilitates
understanding of
cultural, political,
economic, and
urban systems.

47981C4B148540D49D38FECECC795935.description:
Quantitative and qualitative
geographic data are used in
economic, environmental, political,
and social decision making.

518F623A5C23483BB85283023B53519E.description:
Data may be gathered in the field
by organizations (e.g., census
data) or by individuals (e.g.,
interviews, surveys, photography,
informal observations).

FFC0BD401D38467AA2BF42B7B9AE6BAE.description:
Use quantitative
and qualitative
geographic data.

079EAF2E97714790AC2728EEE22BDB65.description:
Field experiences
continue to be
important means of
gathering geographic
information and data.

EA71BD64B6844C5A93A75429AC7E18AA.description:
Geospatial data (e.g., census
data, satellite imagery) is used
at all scales for personal (e.g.,
navigation), business (e.g.,
marketing), and governmental (e.g.,
environmental planning) purposes.

C9BC239A330347DF9D4B756D3D0B280D.description:
Geospatial technologies include
geographic information systems
(GIS), satellite navigation systems
(e.g., global positioning system),
remote sensing, and online
mapping and visualization.

40A82D05AC3842C8A7734264525BC3E7.description:
Geo-spatial
technologies increase
the capability for
gathering and
analyzing geographic
information with
applications to
everyday life.

2F7698469ACC4E84BFCBAE711893C031.description:
Interconnections among
places include exchanges of
natural resources, agricultural
commodities, finished products,
services, people, information,
money, and pollutants.

C6FBD6F85EC24E668F365E8AA7E029C6.description:
Regionalism refers to a group’s
perceived identification with
a particular region at any
scale (e.g., Quebec).

57C6FD57B9314127842AF2E365B32FC6.description:
Regional thinking is applied at
local, national, and global scales.

BF5A3CBECDFE49F7A6EF317BF12A426D.description:
Explain and evaluate
the regionalization
process.

DA272A6F039D445E98A771CC67803C28.description:
World regions may overlap
(e.g., Southeast Asia and Asia)
and often have transitional
boundaries (e.g., North Africa
and Sub-Saharan Africa).

4174063DF5694AB78588276C9AC02F30.description:
World regions are defined for this
course by the maps in the course
curriculum section of the AP Human
Geography Course Description.

B10C2CBA8CEF4BAAB35AE6525043DAD0.description:
Types of regions include formal,
functional, and perceptual.

C12C02075F8849008B5187176AF17E17.description:
Regions are defined on the basis of
one or more unifying characteristics
(e.g., corn belt) or on patterns of
activity (e.g., hinterlands of ports).

7726BEF5EB234D879049FB244417AD47.description:
Define region as a
concept, identify
world regions,
and understand
regionalization
processes.

172912611EEC4253AEB0AC58C572843E.description:
Patterns and processes at
different scales reveal variations
in and different interpretations
of data (e.g., age–sex pyramids,
population density).

ACD11F0764B241F3BF0902273B39A796.description:
Interpret patterns
and processes at
different scales.

609B48D70F0F4750ADDEF34291EB3A8B.description:
Geographical issues include
problems related to human–
environmental interactions (e.g.,
sustainable agriculture); conflict
and cooperation among countries
(e.g., European Union); and
planning and public-policy decision
making (e.g., pronatalist policies).

F31DACF5D9C74F0C81D5BA567BE97532.description:
Use concepts such
as space, place, and
region to examine
geographic issues.

6B49BC8ABE4B4D3292736A93BE69167A.description:
Geographers use models
as generalizations to think
systematically about topics such as
land use (e.g., von Thünen model,
Latin American city model), industrial
location (e.g., Weber model), and
the distribution of settlements (e.g.,
Christaller’s central place theory).

F3308C2AB64A4DDA8A767CF1CD338100.description:
Mathematical formulas and graphs
are used to analyze rates of natural
increase in population, population
doubling time, rank-size rule for
cities, and distance-decay functions.

9D41052C3F3940F387DDBFE4982D5B87.description:
Apply mathematical
formulas and
graphs to interpret
geographic concepts.

AB4B95E4EDB74AE3A64D79E2564D2771.description:
All map projections (e.g.,
Mercator, polar) inevitably distort
spatial relationships (e.g., shape,
area, distance, direction).

7316036389E246E59E6124516A8E6BDB.description:
Types of maps include reference
maps (e.g., physical and political
maps) and thematic maps (e.g.,
choropleth, dot, graduated
symbol, isoline, cartogram).

7DAD8738F04F483A999353724DA6C5FA.description:
Maps are used to represent and
identify spatial patterns and
processes at different scales.

A5371961FC2C4D65BD0014A30ADAEAD6.description:
Use spatial thinking
to analyze the human
organization of space.

2458E5B5208747238D171D93059C4A22.description: Geographical skills provide a foundation for analyzing world patterns and processes

3EE8AAD667BC4276B52B8931C040D4EC.description:
Landscape analysis (e.g., field
observations, photographic
interpretations) provides a context
for understanding the location of
people, places, regions, and events;
human–environment relationships;
and interconnections between
and among places and regions.

E7BF4C957C3C4C2EAFA5B0F6D8590B03.description: Use landsacpe analysis to examine the human organizaiton of space

8FF0A5FABB5046AFBA6577A761B09A8B.description:
Geographical concepts include
location, place, scale, space,
pattern, nature and society,
networks, flows, regionalization,
and globalization.

505D6FBADBFE44F69738FCB5C927C3CA.description: Explain major geographical concepts underlying the geographic perspective

4458228A3FCD43349016960D47DF46DB.description: Geography offers a set of concepts, skills, and tools that facilitate critical thinking and problem solving

D8C2BA4EE2F845CF8CA9B4B24E949ED2.description: Geographic information provides context for understanding spatial relationships and human-environment interaction.

F5DC6751B3A74114BBA0097909467C98.description: Explain the importance of geography as a field of study

B5313532D59D4653B20A716E0CBC0F17.description: Geography, as a field of inquiry looks at the world from a spatial perspective.
